data.title: Tulare County Naturalizations
data.text:
Tulare County Naturalizations - 1 TULARE COUNTY NATURALIZATION RECORDS

In 1987 members of the Sequoia Genealogical Society began the transcription of the naturalization records which they completed in 1991. The cards were then typed into a four volume book format which is available at the Genealogy Room of the Tulare City Library, 113 North F Street, Tulare, CA. The records below are a summary of those records. The book contains much more information and is tied to copies of the actual records kept in the library's back room. The first column of the records below indicates the page on which the information can be found in this four volume work.

All of the index cards were typed, they were copied verbatim, everything on each card was copied, including any note, which had been added. There was evidence that they had been taken from handwritten records. In the case of the name BLISS, for instance, it is typed BLIPS, which indicates the old way to write the double 's'. The name DuBRUTZ, is typed DuBNITZ. Here the old way of writing the 'r' followed by the 'u' looks like the 'ni' except for a dot over the 'i'. These were copied just as they had been typed on the card, even if they were known to be incorrect. There are a couple other instances of this type of error. Mostly these errors are made among the witnesses names.

To obtain copies of the appropriate pages from the book send a self-addressed, stamped envelope; $2.00 plus $.20 per page to the Sequoia Genealogy Society, 113 North F Street, Tulare, CA 93274 or visit the library at that location.

A special thanks goes to Louise Calaway who transcribed all four volunes into a computer database program which is available at the library.

The names can be accessed by choosing the first letter of the individual's surname below or by scrolling down the list.
